owl:Ontology.owl:versionInfo: This is version 2.0 of the TOGAF Content Metamodel ontology. It is based on the Content Metamodel of the TOGAF Version 9.2 standard. See https://pubs.opengroup.org/architecture/togaf9-doc/arch/chap30.html for the complete set of entities, attributes and relationships.

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: User-definable categorization taxonomy for each metamodel entity.
owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:label: has category

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A person, organization, or system that has a role that initiates or interacts with activities; for example, a sales representative who travels to visit customers. Actors may be internal or external to an organization. In the automotive industry, an original equipment manufacturer would be considered an actor by an automotive dealership that interacts with its supply chain activities.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Actor

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A statement of probable fact that has not been fully validated at this stage, due to external constraints. For example, it may be assumed that an existing application will support a certain set of functional requirements, although those requirements may not yet have been individually validated.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Assumption

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A particular ability that a business may possess or exchange to achieve a particular purpose.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Business Capability

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Supports business capabilities through an explicitly defined interface and is explicitly governed by an organization.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Business Service

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A business-focused outcome that is delivered by the completion of one or more work packages. Using a capability-based planning approach, change activities can be sequenced and grouped in order to provide continuous and incremental business value.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Capability

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An external factor that prevents an organization from pursuing particular approaches to meet its goals. For example, customer data is not harmonized within the organization, regionally or nationally, constraining the organization's ability to offer effective customer service.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Constraint

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An agreement between a service consumer and a service provider that establishes functional and non-functional parameters for interaction.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Contract

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A decision-making step with accompanying decision logic used to determine execution approach for a process or to ensure that a process complies with governance criteria. For example, a sign-off control on the purchase request processing process that checks whether the total value of the request is within the sign-off limits of the requester, or whether it needs escalating to higher authority.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Control

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Direction and focus provided by strategic goals and objectives, often to deliver the value proposition characterized in the business model.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Course of Action

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An encapsulation of data that is recognized by a business domain expert as a thing. Logical data entities can be tied to applications, repositories, and services and may be structured according to implementation considerations.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Data Entity

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An external or internal condition that motivates the organization to define its goals. An example of an external driver is a change in regulation or compliance rules which, for example, require changes to the way an organization operates; i.e., Sarbanes-Oxley in the US.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Driver

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An organizational state change that triggers processing events; may originate from inside or outside the organization and may be resolved inside or outside the organization.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Event

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Delivers business capabilities closely aligned to an organization, but not necessarily explicitly governed by the organization. Also referred to as "business function".
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Function

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A statement of difference between two states. Used in the context of gap analysis, where the difference between the Baseline and Target Architecture is identified.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Gap

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A high-level statement of intent or direction for an organization. Typically used to measure success of an organization.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Goal

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The automated elements of a business service. An information system service may deliver or support part or all of one or more business services.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Information System Service

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A place where business activity takes place and can be hierarchically decomposed.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Location

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An encapsulation of application functionality that is independent of a particular implementation. For example, the classification of all purchase request processing applications implemented in an enterprise.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Logical Application Component

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A boundary zone that encapsulates related data entities to form a logical location to be held; for example, external procurement information.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Logical Data Component

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An encapsulation of technology infrastructure that is independent of a particular product. A class of technology product; for example, supply chain management software as part of an Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) suite, or a Commercial Off-The-Shelf (COTS) purchase request processing enterprise service.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Logical Technology Component

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An indicator or factor that can be tracked, usually on an ongoing basis, to determine success or alignment with objectives and goals.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Measure

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A time-bounded milestone for an organization used to demonstrate progress towards a goal; for example, "Increase capacity utilization by 30% by the end of 2019 to support the planned increase in market share".
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Objective

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A self-contained unit of resources with goals, objectives, and measures. Organization units may include external parties and business partner organizations.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Organization Unit

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An application, application module, application service, or other deployable component of functionality. For example, a configured and deployed instance of a Commercial Off-The-Shelf (COTS) Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) supply chain management application.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Physical Application Component

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A boundary zone that encapsulates related data entities to form a physical location to be held. For example, a purchase order business object, comprising purchase order header and item business object nodes.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Physical Data Component

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A specific technology infrastructure product or technology infrastructure product instance. For example, a particular product version of a Commercial Off-The-Shelf (COTS) solution, or a specific brand and version of server.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Physical Technology Component

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A qualitative statement of intent that should be met by the architecture. Has at least a supporting rationale and a measure of importance.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Principle

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A process represents flow of control between or within functions and/or services (depends on the granularity of definition). Processes represent a sequence of activities that together achieve a specified outcome, can be decomposed into sub-processes, and can show operation of a function or service (at next level of detail). Processes may also be used to link or compose organizations, functions, services, and processes.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Process

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Output generated by the business. The business product of the execution of a process.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Product

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A quantitative statement of business need that must be met by a particular architecture or work package.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Requirement

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The usual or expected function of an actor, or the part somebody or something plays in a particular action or event. An actor may have a number of roles.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Role

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A preset configuration of non-functional attributes that may be assigned to a service or service contract.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Service Quality

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A technical capability required to provide enabling infrastructure that supports the delivery of applications.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Technology Service

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A representation of an end-to-end collection of value-adding activities that create an overall result for a customer, stakeholder, or end-user.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Value Stream

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A set of actions identified to achieve one or more objectives for the business. A work package can be a part of a project, a complete project, or a program.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Work Package
